    slots: [
      { time: '8:00 AM', name: 'Train from London Victoria → Seaford', note: 'Take the train from London Victoria to Seaford — about 1.5 hrs with a quick change at Lewes. Trains run every 30 min from Victoria. Buy a return ticket London Victoria to Seaford, then a separate single Eastbourne to London Victoria for the return (you walk one-way along the cliffs). Aim to arrive in Seaford by 9:30–10 AM to make the most of the day.', tag_transport: 'Victoria → Lewes → Seaford · ~1h30m · book on Trainline in advance', tag_tip: 'Wear comfortable walking shoes · bring water and snacks · sunscreen in August' },
      { time: '10:00 AM', name: 'Seaford to Cuckmere Haven', note: 'From Seaford station, walk 10 min to the seafront and head east along the coast path. The white chalk cliffs begin appearing within the first 30 minutes. After about an hour, you reach Cuckmere Haven — where the river meets the Channel, with the famous Coastguard Cottages set against the cliff backdrop. One of the most photographed views in England.', tag_tip: 'Cross at Exceat Bridge (inland), not at the river mouth — currents are unpredictable' },
      { time: '11:30 AM', name: 'Ascending the Seven Sisters', note: 'From Cuckmere Haven, climb up onto the first sister. The trail undulates dramatically — each peak and valley gives a different perspective of the chalk cliffs plunging into the English Channel. The full Seven Sisters run is about 5 miles of ups and downs. August in good weather: the chalk is brilliant white, the sea is deep blue, the grass on top is vivid green.', tag_tip: 'Stay well back from the cliff edges — chalk erodes unpredictably · stick to marked South Downs Way paths' },
      { time: '1:30 PM', name: 'Birling Gap — lunch & beach', note: 'After the seven peaks, descend to Birling Gap — there is a National Trust café here for tea, coffee, soup and sandwiches. The staircase down to the beach is right here: the pebble beach at the base of the white cliffs is extraordinary. Eat, rest, swim if you\'re brave (it\'s the English Channel — cold even in August).', tag_food: 'National Trust café at Birling Gap — soup, sandwiches, scones, tea · open daily', tag_tip: 'Café fills up at lunchtime — arrive before 1 PM or after 2 PM' },
      { time: '3:00 PM', name: 'Beachy Head & the lighthouse', note: 'Continue east past Birling Gap to the Belle Tout lighthouse and then to Beachy Head — the highest chalk sea cliff in Britain at 162 metres. The red-and-white striped Beachy Head lighthouse far below at the waterline is one of the great English coastal views. From the clifftop the view stretches across the Channel on a clear August day.', tag_tip: 'Don\'t miss the viewpoint down to the Beachy Head lighthouse — the best single view of the day' },
      { time: '4:30 PM', name: 'Eastbourne — train back to London', note: 'Descend into Eastbourne (25 min walk along the promenade from the cliff descent to the station). Buy fish and chips or a pint at a pub before the train. Direct trains from Eastbourne to London Victoria run regularly — about 1 hr 30 min. Back in London by 7 PM.', tag_transport: 'Eastbourne → London Victoria direct · ~1h30m · trains every 30 min', tag_food: 'Fish and chips or pub pint in Eastbourne before the train home' },
    ]
  },
  {
    date: 'Monday, Aug 24',
    title: '🎤 Ariana Grande — Eternal Sunshine Tour',
    color: '--concert',
    slots: [
      { time: 'Morning', name: 'Kensington — Natural History Museum', note: 'Free entry. The Natural History Museum is one of the finest in the world — the Hintze Hall with the blue whale skeleton, the dinosaur exhibition, the Earth gallery. Take your time; this is a full morning.', tag_food: 'Lunch at the museum café or grab a picnic from Whole Foods nearby' },
      { time: '2:00 PM', name: 'Hyde Park & Kensington Gardens', note: 'Walk through Hyde Park to Kensington Gardens — the Serpentine lake, the Albert Memorial, Kensington Palace. In August the park is beautiful: deck chairs, boats on the lake, Londoners at their most relaxed.' },
